is facing up. Identify the two muscles of the lateral compartment, the fibularis longus and fibularis brevis. Know that these muscles were previously know as the peroneus longus and brevis. Despite the fact that they were renamed 50 years ago, clinicians may still refer to them using these obsolete names.
Notice that the fibularis longus arises from the proximal fibula, and the fibularis brevis arises deep to the longus, from the distal fibula. Follow the tendons of these muscle around the lateral malleolus. Note the attachment of the fibularis brevis to the base of the fifth metatarsal, and observe that the fibularis longus disappears from view into the sole of the foot. As illustrated, the fibularis longus tendon crosses the sole of the foot to attach at its medial side. 
These muscles pull upward on the lateral aspect of the foot. What is their action? Don’t click here until you think of your answer     .
